    <item>
      <title>On Color Palettes</title>
      <link>http://localhost:1313/posts/color-palettes/</link>
      <pubDate>Tue, 25 Nov 2025 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>http://localhost:1313/posts/color-palettes/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;Bought a new book on color theory today. There&amp;rsquo;s something meditative about limiting yourself to five colors. Constraints breed creativity.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;The book is Josef Albers&amp;rsquo; &amp;ldquo;Interaction of Color.&amp;rdquo; Published in 1963, still relevant today. His core insight: we never see colors in isolation. Every hue is influenced by its neighbors.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Put a gray square on a yellow background and it looks purple. Put the same gray on a purple background and it looks yellow. The color itself hasn&amp;rsquo;t changed—only the context.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
